frameDefinitions: Item-1 and Item-2 are compatible with each other if they can exist or function together in some context without problems, conflict, or other undesirable situation.
A Controlling_entity, Controlling_situation, or Controlling_variable control a Dependent_entity, Dependent_situation, or Dependent_variable.
This frame concerns Acts and State_of_
These words refer to an Agent joining Parts to form a Whole.

The words in this frame describe situations in which a Perpetrator carries off and holds the Victim against his or her will by force. '' 'Two men kidnapped a Millwall soccer club employee, police said last night.'
One linguistic unit, Sign_1, has a relation to another linguistic unit, Sign_2.
frameExamples: Make sure your site is <t>compatible</t> with any browser.
A lot of people suspect that blocking savers' access to their money <t>violates</t> the new constitution's explicit ban on compulsory loans to the government.
Two men <t>kidnapped</t> a Millwall soccer club employee, police said last night.
listRoleDefinitions: The Frame Element <fen>Item_1</fen> marks the grammatically more prominent of the two entities, i.e.the subject in active clauses, when they are expressed separately.
The Frame Element <fen>Item_2</fen> marks the grammatically less prominent of the <fen>Items</fen> when they are expressed separately.
This role is used when the <fen>Items</fen> are expressed jointly in a phrase, either a plural or a coordinated NP.
This Frame Element is used for expressions that indicate a <fen>Parameter</fen> or respect in which the <fen>Items</fen> are said to be compatible, not in conflict.
A thing or person whose behavior controls a <fen>Dependent_entity</fen>, <fen>Dependent_situation</fen>, or <fen>Dependent_variable</fen>.
An entity, usually a thing, that is influenced in its behavior by a <fen>Controlling_entity</fen> or an <fen>Controlling_situation</fen>.
The <fex name='tim'>Time</fex> at which the controlling occurs.
The location at which the controlling occurs.
The <fen>Protagonist</fen>'s behavior is in or out of compliance with norms.
This role identifies the <fen>Act</fen> that is judged to be in or out of compliance with the <fen>Norm</fen>s.
A <fen>State_of_affairs</fen> may violate a law or rule.
This role identifies the rules or <fen>Norm</fen>s that ought to guide a person's behavior.
This role identifies the <fen>Time</fen>  when the act of compliance or non-compliance occurs.

In causative uses of these verbs there is an <fen>Agent</fen> responsible for amalgamating the <fen>Parts</fen>. The <fen>Agent</fen> is generally the External Argument (or the object of a PP-by in passives).
This  role identifies <fen>Whole</fen> as the entity resulting from combination of <fen>Parts</fen>.  When overtly expressed, it is usually a PP Complement (often headed by into).
This role identifies the <fen>Parts</fen> entities being combined, and is often expressed in a single plural NP, usually the direct object of a verb.
This role identifies the first of two <fen>Parts</fen> mentioned. It  is most often the NP-Object of a verb.
This role identifies the second of two <fen>Parts</fen> mentioned. It is usually a PP Complement.
The time at which the amalgamation occurs.
The location that the event occurs.
The <fen>Perpetrator</fen> is the person (or other agent) who carries off and holds the <fen>Victim</fen> against his or her will.
The <fen>Victim</fen> is the person who is carried off and held against his/her will.
When the kidnapping occurs.
Where the kidnapping takes place.
FN: a linguistic unit that carries semantic, phonological or syntactic information.
FN: a linguistic unit

Chuck merged <fex>the corpora</fex> into a database.

The workkmen joined the annex <fex>to the main building</fex>.

In one sense, dog is a hyponym of <fex>itself</fex>.
